Postman Response Assertions Within postman, test assertions can be included to check the validity of the API request and response objects. Postman test assertions follows a BDD style and are based on the capabilities of the Chai Assertion Library. Read more about Chai at https://www.chaijs.com/api/bdd/
 Assert status pm.test("Must fail with response status", function () { pm.response.to.have.status(400); });   Assert json response body element pm.test("Verify jwt issuer", function () { var jsonData = pm.response.json(); pm.expect(jsonData.code).to.eql("CODE-001"); });   Assert absence of a json element pm.test("Verify if users has an entitlement", function(){ var data = pm.response.json(); pm.expect(data).to.not.have.ownPropertyDescriptor('entitlements'); })   Check if an integer data value is above a specific value pm.test("Verify if users exists", function(){ var data = pm.response.json(); pm.expect(data.paging.total).to.be.above(1); })   Check integer equality pm.test("Verify if users exists", function(){ var data = pm.response.json(); pm.expect(data.paging.total).to.be.equal(0); })   Decode a JWT There will be scenarios in which you want to check the validity of a Bearer token represented as a JWT token
 As you would be familiar JWT tokens, it is a concatenated string of Base64 encoded representation of JWT header, payload(aka claims) and signature.We define a simple function to do a split based on JWT delimiter(.) and then pick the payload(claims) value and decode the Base64 value using atob function in javascript. Then the structure can be parsed using a JSON object parser function.
 function jwt_decode(jwt) { var parts = jwt.split('.'); // header, payload, signature return JSON.parse(atob(parts[1])); } var data = JSON.parse(responseBody); var decodedJwtClaim = jwt_decode(data.transactionJwt) console.log("Extract txnId from jwtclaim + ", decodedJwt.content.txnId)   Set extracted value in environment variable var data = JSON.parse(responseBody); postman.setEnvironmentVariable("userUuid", data.uuid); pm.environment.set("txnId", data.content.txnId)   More reference is available at Postman official site
 Skip Request based on
 //loop for x times the same test randomCounter = parseInt(randomCounter) + 1 postman.setGlobalVariable('lockOutCount', randomCounter); console.log(randomCounter) if( randomCounter &lt; 6) { console.log("rerunning flow"); console.log(postman.getGlobalVariable('lockOutCount')); postman.setNextRequest("AuthN -Password authentication - wrong password#1"); } else { postman.setGlobalVariable('lockOutCount', 0); }

Newman Newman is the commandline equivalent of postman gui
 sudo npm install -g newman; cd postman-snippets; ./run_workflows.sh json envs/env.postman_environment.json   Iterate through your postman scripts
 #!/usr/bin/env bash ENVIRONMENT=envs/env.postman_environment.json REPORT_TYPE=html FLIP_POLICIES_BACK_TO_CORE=false if [ -n "$1" ]; then REPORT_TYPE=$1 fi if [ -n "$2" ]; then ENVIRONMENT=$2 fi if [ -d reports ]; then rm -r reports fi mkdir -p reports rm reports/postman.log 2&gt; /dev/null for file in workflow-collections/*.json; do WORKFLOW=$(echo $file | sed -e "s/^workflow-collections\//report-/" -e "s/.json//") echo "Executing Identityt $WORKFLOW" newman run $file -e $ENVIRONMENT --insecure --bail --reporters cli,$REPORT_TYPE --reporter-$REPORT_TYPE-export reports/$WORKFLOW.$REPORT_TYPE | tee -a reports/postman.log retVal=$? if [ ! $retVal -eq 0 ]; then echo "Error on $file" #exit $retVal fi done

GIT Create Tag To create a tag on your current branch, run this:
 git tag &lt;tagname&gt;
 This will create a local tag with the current state of the branch you are on. When pushing to your remote repo, tags are NOT included by default. You will need to explicitly say that you want to push your tags to your remote repo:
 git push origin —tags
   Note  This command will push all the tags in your local machine. Try to avoid using this unless you want to purposefully push all the tags available on your machine. One of the problems could be someone could have removed remote tags, but you will repush tags from your local repo, in case you had pulled it down before deletion     Or if you just want to push a single tag:
 git push origin &lt;tag&gt;
